etymologies: early 16th century; earliest use found in Gavin Douglas (c1476–1522), poet and bishop of Dunkeld. From down- + come, after to come down and downcome

definitions: The action or an act of coming down; descent from a higher place or position; downfall; humiliation.
A pipe or tube which conveys liquid or gases downwards, especially in a blast furnace; = "downcomer".
